WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.690 --> 00:00:05.260
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:23.170 --> 00:00:24.620
&gt;&gt; Hong Ta-Moore: My
name is Hong Ta-Moore.

00:00:24.620 --> 00:00:27.940
Reference librarian for
Southeast Asian collection

00:00:27.940 --> 00:00:30.400
in the Asian division.

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:33.000
Thank you for joining
us today for a lecture

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.240
on shadow theater in Indonesia.

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:41.730
In collaboration with
the embassy of Indonesia,

00:00:41.730 --> 00:00:45.760
the Asian division is honored to
have two distinguished experts

00:00:45.760 --> 00:00:50.140
in the field of Balinese
shadow theater to talk to us

00:00:50.140 --> 00:00:53.830
about this ancient form of
storytelling through the use

00:00:53.830 --> 00:00:57.030
of puppets and shadows.

00:00:57.030 --> 00:00:58.630
Due to time constraints,

00:00:58.630 --> 00:01:01.550
please hold your
questions until the end.

00:01:01.550 --> 00:01:07.450
With us today we have Dr. Andy
McGraw, an associate professor

00:01:07.450 --> 00:01:12.210
of music at the University
of Richmond, Virginia.

00:01:12.210 --> 00:01:16.850
He received his Ph.D.
in ethnomusicology

00:01:16.850 --> 00:01:24.670
at Wesleyan University in 2005
and has published extensively

00:01:24.670 --> 00:01:30.890
on traditional and experimental
music in southeast Asia.

00:01:30.890 --> 00:01:34.940
His performances and
collaborations have appeared

00:01:34.940 --> 00:01:40.940
on the [inaudible]
importer labels.

00:01:40.940 --> 00:01:44.390
He is the author of
"Radical Traditions.

00:01:44.390 --> 00:01:49.230
Reimagining Culture in
Bali's Contemporary Music"

00:01:49.230 --> 00:01:53.770
which was published in 2013
by Oxford University Press,

00:01:53.770 --> 00:01:59.590
and co-editor of "Performing
Indonesia" published in 2016

00:01:59.590 --> 00:02:02.350
by the Smithsonian Publications.

00:02:02.350 --> 00:02:07.190
His current monograph
project entitled "Good Music,

00:02:07.190 --> 00:02:15.410
Sound Ethics is an Ethnography
of Music as Ethical Practice

00:02:15.410 --> 00:02:18.210
in Four Alternative
Communities."

00:02:18.210 --> 00:02:23.760
A monastery, jail,
commune, and village.

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:29.280
Also joining us is
Mr. Gusti Sudarta,

00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:34.280
a Balinese shadow master,
musician, composer,

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:37.350
dancer, and choreographer.

00:02:37.350 --> 00:02:41.880
At age six, Mr. Sudarta began
extensive and continuous study

00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:46.800
of traditional Balinese
performing arts, music, dance,

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:51.030
and theater with family
members and master performers

00:02:51.030 --> 00:02:53.330
in the villages of [inaudible].

00:02:54.480 --> 00:03:04.630
He has been a permanent
faculty member at the Institute

00:03:04.630 --> 00:03:10.210
of the Arts in [inaudible]
since 1991.

00:03:10.210 --> 00:03:14.630
He is a renown performer of
Balinese traditional forms

00:03:14.630 --> 00:03:18.830
and is at the forefront of
contemporary experimentation.

00:03:18.830 --> 00:03:23.220
He has performed extensively
in Asia, Europe, Australia,

00:03:23.220 --> 00:03:26.460
and America conducting
three world tours

00:03:26.460 --> 00:03:31.460
with [inaudible] project
between 1998 and 2003.

00:03:31.460 --> 00:03:34.060
He is currently pursuing
his Ph.D.

00:03:34.060 --> 00:03:37.450
at SIS [inaudible] Indonesia.

00:03:37.450 --> 00:03:41.240
Please join me to
welcome our guests.

00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:43.040
Thank you.

00:03:43.040 --> 00:03:51.370
[ Applause ]

00:03:51.370 --> 00:03:52.670
&gt;&gt; Andy McGraw: Hi, folks.

00:03:52.670 --> 00:03:54.690
Thanks for coming.

00:03:54.690 --> 00:03:57.950
So this is how this
talk is going to go.

00:03:57.950 --> 00:04:03.850
We're going to demonstrate
some traditional shadow theater

00:04:03.850 --> 00:04:07.660
techniques and talk about
a traditional performance

00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:11.040
that has informed
some experimental work

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:13.240
that Pat Gutsi has been doing.

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:17.300
And what we'll do first is I'll
give a really brief introduction

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:22.580
on Indonesia and Bali
and shadow theater,

00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:24.660
and then I'll hand
it over to Pat Gusti.

00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:27.410
He's not completely
fluent in English

00:04:27.410 --> 00:04:30.530
so the way we put this paper
together was yesterday I sat

00:04:30.530 --> 00:04:34.680
down with him and
interviewed him on this topic,

00:04:34.680 --> 00:04:36.150
wrote up the notes in English,

00:04:36.150 --> 00:04:37.850
and he will be reading
them today,

00:04:37.850 --> 00:04:40.540
and I'll be running the slides
and showing the video and kind

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:44.580
of coming back and maybe
helping pronunciation if

00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:49.440
and when it needs a little
bit of clarification.

00:04:50.610 --> 00:04:54.060
So I'm assuming if
you're in the room,

00:04:54.060 --> 00:04:56.870
you know where the
nation of Indonesia is.

00:04:56.870 --> 00:05:01.020
I don't need to go very
deeply into this, I hope,

00:05:01.020 --> 00:05:05.080
other than to remind you
that it's very large,

00:05:05.080 --> 00:05:08.680
very complicated nation with a
lot of different ethnicities.

00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:14.460
A lot of different languages and
many, many waves of migrations.

00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:21.590
So a lot of religious
syncretism, cultural syncretism,

00:05:21.590 --> 00:05:27.550
and in Bali and Java, a really
complicated mix of Buddhists,

00:05:27.550 --> 00:05:33.500
Hindu, and Islamic
ideas, cultural practices,

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:39.410
and mixture with
indigenous animism.

00:05:39.410 --> 00:05:43.120
That's all I'm going
to go with that.

00:05:43.120 --> 00:05:46.370
We could spend the rest of the
talk on it but I get a sense

00:05:46.370 --> 00:05:47.980
that you already know this.

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:52.090
Here is a sense of
Bali and its regencies.

00:05:52.090 --> 00:05:55.420
Pat Gutsi is from the village
of [inaudible] and [inaudible]

00:05:55.420 --> 00:05:59.970
which was the seat of
the Balinese kingdom

00:05:59.970 --> 00:06:05.640
when the military
expedition from [inaudible]

00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:11.020
in the 14th century came over
to Bali and changed a lot

00:06:11.020 --> 00:06:14.350
of Balinese culture and
introduced new religious

00:06:14.350 --> 00:06:17.080
and cultural practices.

00:06:18.610 --> 00:06:24.060
So, Pat Gutsi and I have
been working together

00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:27.640
since about 2001, 2002.

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:32.830
So he is one of my teachers of
the rather specialized music

00:06:32.830 --> 00:06:35.000
that accompanies the
Balinese shadow play.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:37.770
It's called [inaudible],
but we've done a lot

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:41.310
of collaborations
together over the years.

00:06:41.310 --> 00:06:45.940
And we were just
performing this weekend

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:47.930
at the IluminAsia Festival

00:06:47.930 --> 00:06:53.340
over at the Smithsonian Saturday
night and then Sunday morning

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:56.380
and then over at the Kennedy
Center Sunday evening.

00:06:56.380 --> 00:07:00.620
And we'll show you
some footage from that.

00:07:00.620 --> 00:07:05.830
I assume also that you know WMR.

00:07:05.830 --> 00:07:13.760
So could we show the traditional
shadow puppets of Indonesia.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:17.930
It's buffalo hide
that's been perforated,

00:07:17.930 --> 00:07:20.700
cut, and then painted.

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:24.800
Why do they paint it when
you only see the shadow?

00:07:24.800 --> 00:07:30.350
It's both to help remind the
puppeteer or the [inaudible]

00:07:30.350 --> 00:07:34.600
of the character
traits of the puppets,

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:39.570
but also because the audience
often sits on both sides

00:07:39.570 --> 00:07:42.860
of the screen and they move
around the performances.

00:07:42.860 --> 00:07:45.890
And after our talk, you
can get a chance to come up

00:07:45.890 --> 00:07:48.380
and check them out more closely.

00:07:48.380 --> 00:07:54.060
So what we thought what we would
do is actually open up this talk

00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:57.700
by Pat Gutsi doing the
traditional [inaudible].

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:00.460
The [inaudible] is
the tree of life.

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:03.880
Sometimes called the [inaudible]
in the [inaudible] tradition,

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:08.760
and it dances to create
the universe of the play.

00:08:08.760 --> 00:08:10.210
So we found what we would open

00:08:10.210 --> 00:08:13.200
up with a traditional
[inaudible] performance

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:15.520
and then what's called
the [inaudible]

00:08:15.520 --> 00:08:18.950
or the fragrant forest
which is the scene

00:08:18.950 --> 00:08:22.810
in which the [inaudible]
recites poetry

00:08:22.810 --> 00:08:26.850
in the [inaudible]
language that sets the scene

00:08:26.850 --> 00:08:31.250
and introduces the main
characters before Pat Gutsi

00:08:31.250 --> 00:08:33.070
reads his section of the paper.

00:08:33.070 --> 00:08:39.790
So what we'll do here is we'll
play -- so we have some music.

00:08:39.790 --> 00:08:47.110
We'll play; if this
works, we'll play the scene

00:08:47.110 --> 00:08:49.120
from the Kennedy Center
performance yesterday.

00:08:49.120 --> 00:08:52.720
So we had some music to
accompany the [inaudible] here.

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:54.500
Oh, error loading media file.

00:08:54.500 --> 00:08:55.800
Wonderful.

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:57.100
Nice. Yes.

00:08:57.100 --> 00:08:58.400
Let's see.

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:03.370
Let's try it one more time.

00:09:03.370 --> 00:09:07.200
There we go.

