00:12:13.970 --> 00:12:15.270
So there were moments in there

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:23.930
where I think you can
see it represents wind,

00:12:23.930 --> 00:12:28.840
represents water,
represents land.

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:32.470
And then what he would do
is he would sing the scene

00:12:32.470 --> 00:12:36.640
for [inaudible] and he
chose some special texts

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:41.190
for these performances based
on a legend called Sutasoma.

00:12:41.190 --> 00:12:43.100
A story called Sutasoma.

00:12:43.100 --> 00:12:44.940
Normally it's a different
text that's used,

00:12:44.940 --> 00:12:50.830
but he took this text from
this story, and the author

00:12:50.830 --> 00:12:53.370
or the scribe that
set this version

00:12:53.370 --> 00:12:58.900
of Sutasoma has been informing
Pat Gutsi's experimental work.

00:12:58.900 --> 00:13:02.420
So we wanted to start from there
so you have a sense of the kind

00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:06.050
of evolution from
the traditional text

00:13:06.050 --> 00:13:09.770
to the experimental work that
we'll show later at the end.

00:13:09.770 --> 00:13:12.170
And I'll slide through the
translations of the [inaudible]

00:13:12.170 --> 00:13:15.520
that he's going to sing.

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:22.510
That would be the next
session of the shadow play.

